-- Serb March Foreign-Exchange Reserves Rise to 11.8 Billion Euros
-- B y   G o r d a n a   F i l i p o v i c
-- 2013-04-12T10:29:53Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-04-12/serb-march-foreign-exchange-reserves-rise-to-11-8-billion-euros.html
Serbiaâ€™s foreign-exchange reserves
rose 1.2 percent in March from the previous month as banks set
aside cash in mandatory reserves and the government borrowed in
euros on the local market.  Reserves advanced to 11.84 billion euros ($15.45 billion),
the Belgrade-based Narodna Banka Srbije said in an e-mailed
statement today. Inflows included 131.5 million euros set aside
by banks to meet reserve-requirement levels, 81.5 million euros
in loans and 50 million euros the government borrowed at home.  Serbia repaid 141 million euros to external creditors last
month and 46.8 million euros to the  International Monetary Fund .  Net reserves, excluding the money commercial lenders keep
with the central bank and funds from the IMF, rose to 7.69
billion euros from 7.6 billion in February, the bank said.  Interbank foreign-currency trading rose 15.5 percent on the
month, to 790.4 million euros, while the dinar depreciated a
nominal 0.4 percent against the euro in March.  To contact the reporter on this story:
